ABOUT THE EVENT
The We Are Samoa Gala is proud to be a platform that will benefit several initiatives that will serve the Pacific Islander Community through general education scholarships, performing arts scholarships, and continuing to build awareness on the burden of type 2 diabetes and heart disease on the Pacific Islander community.

• General education scholarships for Pacific Islanders students (through the National Pacific Islander Network, 501c3) 
• The Jerome Grey Performing Arts Fund to support Pacific Islander students pursuing a career in the arts 
• Create awareness and build outreach programs for the Pacific Islander community on the importance of the burden of diabetes on our community

Unfortunately, there is no cookie cutter recipe for designing a successful social movement that brings about institutional change. Scholars throughout the world have tried to delineate some essential elements but, to this day, disagree on many of them.  Although there is no consensus, there are many plausible theories that explain these social phenomena that are proliferating now, more than ever before.
 
Today, I want to highlight one perspective in particular, formulated by Erica Chenoweth, political  science professor at Harvard University. After looking over hundreds of social and political campaigns for the past century, she suggested that for a social movement to be truly influential it has to yield almost immediate results, be generally peaceful, and engage at least 3.5% of the population.
 
Do you agree or disagree?
 
Source: The '3.5% rule': How a small minority can change the world, BBC, May 2019

Most Americans probably don't know a lot about a rule in the U.S. Senate known as the "filibuster," but they should. Why? As was made painfully clear during FRC's Pray Vote Stand broadcast last night, the filibuster is the only thing standing in the way of America ceasing to be the free country that we know and love due to the disturbing policies that the extreme Left wants to force through the Senate and impose on all Americans without compromise.<U+2060>
<U+2060>
In a country that is politically split down the middle, collaboration and dialogue is what we need more of, not less of. Even so, more and more politicians on the Left are hypocritically calling for an end to the filibuster now that they have the slimmest possible majority in the Senate, even though the Left has been using the filibuster to their advantage for over 200 years whenever they weren't in the majority.<U+2060>
<U+2060>
It used to be that the Senate required an even higher bar to pass legislation—a two-thirds majority to end debate, instead of the 60 votes they changed it to in 1975. Now, instead of working to find middle ground, Democrats want to blow up the entire system and let a simple majority rule. But that's not what the founders intended. They wanted conversation, give-and-take, and cooperation. And if unity is what Joe Biden's party actually wants, then silencing the minority party is hardly the best way to go about it.<U+2060>
<U+2060>
Wednesday, one of the moderate Democrats holding the line on the filibuster, Senator Kyrsten Sinema (D-Ariz.) told the Wall Street Journal, "When you have a place that's broken and not working, and many would say that's the Senate today, I don't think the solution is to erode the rules. I think the solution is for senators to change their behavior and begin to work together, which is what the country wants us to do."<U+2060>
<U+2060>
